subSubSection.paragraph:
Body elongate oval, moderately convex, dorsum with white pubescence (
Figs 11a–f
). Head black or blackish brown (
Fig. 11f
), sometimes yellowish brown (
Fig. 11c
), antennae and mouthparts yellowish brown, tip of mandibles dark brown. Pronotum yellowish brown, scutellar shield dark brown. Elytra black with narrowly apical margins yellowish brown (
Figs 11b, 11e
). Prothoracic hypomeron and prosternum yellowish brown. Mesoventrite and elytral epipleurae dark brown. Metaventrite black. Legs yellowish brown.

Head with fine frontal punctures, as large as eye facets, 0.5–1.0 diameters apart. Eyes densely faceted, interocular distance about 0.2 times of head width (
Figs 11c, 11f
). Pronotal punctures slightly larger than those on frons, 1.0–1.5 diameters apart. Surface of elytra with punctures much larger than those on pronotum, separated by 1.0–2.0 diameters.

Abdominal postcoxal lines complete and moderately recurved, reaching 4/5 length of ventrite 1 (
Fig. 11g
), area enclosed by the lines finely and sparsely punctate, irregularly distributed, broadly smooth along the lines; ventrite 1 with coarse and sparse punctures at middle, uniformly distributed.

Male genitalia. Penis stout, base of penis strongly broadened, basal half to proximal part swollen with membranous appendage, apex slightly curved inward, narrowing to apex in lateral view (
Fig. 11h
); tegmen with penis guide widest at base, subtriangular in inner view (
Fig. 11j
), slightly shorter than 1/2 length of parameres; parameres stout and oval with several setae at apex and inner side in lateral view (
Fig. 11i
).
